      <title>The Proper Serving Temperatures for Red Wine</title>
      <link>http://www.stainless-steel-coffee-mugs.com/the-proper-serving-temperatures-for-red-wine/</link>
      <comments>http://www.stainless-steel-coffee-mugs.com/the-proper-serving-temperatures-for-red-wine/#comments</comments>
      <pubDate>Sun, 09 Oct 2011 02:32:35 +0000</pubDate>
      <dc:creator>Guest</dc:creator>
      <category><![CDATA[Cool Articles]]></category>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">http://www.stainless-steel-coffee-mugs.com/the-proper-serving-temperatures-for-red-wine/</guid>
      <description>There are various myths and misconceptions concerning the best way to serve red wine. The most pervasive fallacies fall into two categories: The correct serving temperature. Whether it is best to decant your wine, and if so, the appropriate way to perform the decanting. Let&amp;#8217;s look at the first category, the suitable temperature red wine [...]&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/stainless-steel-coffee-mugs/Stainless_Steel_Coffee_Mugs-The_Proper_Serving_Temperatures_for_Red_Wine.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>There are various myths and misconceptions concerning the best way  to serve red wine. The most pervasive fallacies fall into  two categories:</p>
<ol>
<li>The correct serving temperature.</li>
<li>Whether it is best to decant your wine, and if so, the appropriate way to perform  the decanting.</li>
</ol>
<p>Let&#8217;s look at the first category, the suitable temperature red wine should be served at,&nbsp; first. &#8220;Room temperature&#8221; is not an precise description of the temperature at which any wine ought to be served.   As a basic guideline, topflight, full-bodied reds are drunk  at higher temperatures than other wines, but even the best Bordeaux&#8211;and other of the highest  quality reds&#8211;should be drunk  in a temperature range between approximately 64 to 68   Fahrenheit. Whichis a lot  cooler than the 72 degrees usually considered  to be optimal room temperature. Burgundy, and other high-quality <a title="Pinot Noir - To Decant or not to Decant?" href="http://santabarbarawinetours.org/pinot-noir-to-decant-or-not-to-decant/" target="_blank">Pinot Noir</a>s, should be poured  at in between 62 to 64 degrees, and lighter or more ordinary reds like Chianti, Zinfandel or Cotes du Rhone, should be drunk at approximately 57 to 62 degrees. Red table wine is ideal served from approximately 54 to 56 degrees, whilst Beaujolais is one red which should be served chilled, from approximately 51 to 55   Fahrenheit.</p>
<p>Why don&#8217;t we  examine  the second category of common confusion. Decanting, or the act of transferring your wine from the bottle to a decanter, serves two purposes: to eliminate any sediment (solid pieces of color pigment and tannins that have bonded together during ageing) that may be present in the bottle; and to aerate, or oxygenate the wine.   Sediment may be present in some bottles of red wine, especially in more mature wines. It&#8217;s best  to keep a bottle of wine you&#8217;re preparing to pour still, preferably standing, for a few hours ahead of uncorking  it, to let any sediment settle to the bottom. Once you do uncork it, you can either cautiously pour the wine into a decanter, making sure not to let any sediment follow the wine into its new container, or just pour the wine straight into glasses&#8211;again, taking care   the sediment stays in the bottle, and only the wine goes into your glass.</p>
<p>When it comes to  aeration, the common wisdom is that you should open a bottle of red wine an hour or so before pouring, to &#8220;let it breathe.&#8221; The issue with this idea is that, because wine bottles possess narrow necks, simply uncorking a bottle exposes just a tiny surface area of wine to the air, and so does not actually let the wine breathe, or in much more technical terms, does not encourage substantial oxidation of the wine. Which is why most decanters are broad at the bottom; this design exposes a wide surface area of wine to the air.</p>
<p>The greater question  though, is whether or not it&#8217;s a good idea  to  decant a particular wine at all. In other words,  do all red wines improve with oxidation?   The   answer to that question  is, &#8220;no.&#8221; The purpose of aeration is to soften highly tannic reds&#8211;for example a top-drawer  Barolo or Syrah&#8211;to soften the tannins and let the wine&#8217;s flavors and complexity &#8220;open up,&#8221; especially in the case of comparatively young wines. A mature wine, on the other hand, can be very frail, and by decanting it, you may just be permitting its bouquet and flavors to dissipate. One kind of red wine that is normally not decanted is Pinot Noir. Good Pinot Noir, particularly Burgundy, is a extremely aromatic, delicate red. Unless it&#8217;s relatively young, it best poured from the bottle directly into a Burgundy glass.</p>
<p>That brings us to  the issue of which kind of glasses are ideal for serving red wine. As you may have  already guessed,&nbsp; there are distinct glasses created with Burgundy specifically in mind. These are large volume, balloon-shaped glasses that enable the drinker to more fully  enjoy Burgundy&#8217;s great bouquet. These glasses should only be employed for top-notch Burgundy, or other top-notch  Pinot Noirs, due to the fact, if used for a&nbsp; more pedestrain Pinot, they can just serve to make the wines ordinariness that much more noticeable. Another red wine that has its own special glass is Bordeaux. These are also high volume glasses but, rather than being balloon-shaped, as Burgundy glasses are, they have vertical  sides &#8211;the so as to encourage oxidation. These are the best glasses for serving the best Bordeaux and other topflight, full-bodied, tannic reds. Lesser wines ought to be served in standard-sized  glasses which should not have a tendency to emphasize the wine&#8217;s deficiencies.</p>
<p>In summary, how red wine is served mainly depends on what type of red wine it is, however, in addition to which glasses to use, there are actually just three items to take into account: you should serve a  wine at its recommended serving temperature; sediment can be an issue with red wine, so if there is sediment present, let it settle to the bottom   prior to pouring; youthful, full-bodied, tannic reds  generally benefit from extensive aeration, so it&#8217;s advisable  to decant them. Mature reds, on the other hand, have already mellowed by way of aging, and may be too frail for such treatment, while Pinot Noir is one red varietal that is typically not decanted.</p>
<p>If you&#8217;d like to learn a lot much more about wine,&nbsp; particularly <a title="Santa Barbara Wine Tours" href="http://santabarbarawinetours.org/">wine tours in Santa Barbara</a> County, then drop by my website <a title="Santa Barbara Wine Tours" href="http://santabarbarawinetours.org/">Santa Barbara Wine Tours</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
